**surprise_party** — Alice, Chris, and a rotating Friend share one group chat.

Alice and the Friend are organizing a surprise party for Chris. Alice knows
the `(where, when)` of the gathering and needs the Friend to understand that
the gathering is actually a surprise party for Chris — without Chris
figuring out that he's the guest of honor. The where/when itself can be
discussed openly; only the surprise-party-for-Chris nature is secret. The
Friend slot is filled by a fresh agent with a different name every round;
the Friend has no memory of prior rounds and starts every round cold. Chris
stays in the chat from round 1 onwards and accumulates context across every
round.

Both the Friend and Chris each have a `submit_guess` tool that takes a
freetext guess. An LLM judge checks whether the guess shows the guesser has
figured out that Alice is organizing a surprise party for Chris. The round
ends as soon as anyone guesses correctly:

* Friend correct → round success, swap in a new Friend, continue.
* Chris correct → round failure, Chris is replaced with a fresh agent
  next round AND a new `(where, when)` gathering is picked — Alice has
  to start over with a different cover plan.
* Wall-clock timeout with no correct guess → round failure.

